    <segment id="1" parent="46" relname="background">One of the links on our HCI website was to Vincent Flanders Web 
Pages that Suck.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="41" relname="span">  The name of the site sort of jumped out at me</segment>
    <segment id="20" parent="40" relname="span"> and I 
thought it would be more of a joke than anything else.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="20" relname="elaboration">  The site has a 
look and feel that is hard to take serious;</segment>
    <segment id="21" parent="46" relname="span"> however, I found that it 
contained a lot of useful web design information.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="43" relname="span">  The following are 
some web design concepts I found under the section titled The 
Biggest Web Design Mistakes of 2004.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="18" relname="preparation">  Vincent Flanders wrote,</segment>
    <segment id="18" parent="30" relname="span">

Write these two sentences where you can see them as you&apos;re working 
on your computer:</segment>
    <segment id="22" parent="29" relname="list">
1. The only reason my web site exists is to solve my customers&apos; 
problems.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="29" relname="list">
2. What problems does the page I&apos;m looking at solve?</segment>
    <segment id="15" parent="42" relname="span">


You should be able to look at the home page of any site and figure out 
what the site is about within four seconds.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="15" relname="otherwise"> If you can&apos;t, your site has 
failed.</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="45" relname="span"> 

All web navigation must answer:</segment>
    <segment id="23" parent="31" relname="list">
Where am I?</segment>
    <segment id="16" parent="31" relname="list">
Where have I been?</segment>
    <segment id="17" parent="31" relname="list">
Where can I go next</segment>
    <segment id="33" parent="31" relname="list">
Where&apos;s the Home Page</segment>
    <segment id="32" parent="31" relname="list">
Where&apos;s the Home Page </segment>
    <segment id="19" parent="24" relname="concession">

Yes, it&apos;s called a web page,</segment>
    <segment id="24" parent="38" relname="span"> but that doesn&apos;t mean you have to cram all 
your material on one page.</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="24" relname="volitional-cause">  Most folks don&apos;t like to scroll.</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="25" relname="volitional-cause"> 


It&apos;s very easy to keep adding material to your home page</segment>
    <segment id="25" parent="39" relname="span"> until it gets 
out of control.</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="34" relname="span"> Smaller business sites are especially susceptible</segment>
    <segment id="26" parent="11" relname="volitional-cause"> because 
they fear they&apos;ll miss a sale.</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="37" relname="span"> 

With so much content vying for attention its initially impossible for the 
eye to settle on one thing.</segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="35" relname="conjunction"> People get confused</segment>
    <segment id="27" parent="35" relname="conjunction"> and people leave.</segment>
    <segment id="14" parent="36" relname="span"> Pages 
with lots of disparate material means you have failed to organize your 
site properly</segment>
    <segment id="28" parent="14" relname="volitional-result"> -- probably a combination of not planning your site and 
poor navigation.</segment>
